00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.189
it's just a topic that you've been interested in

19
00:00:58.189 --> 00:01:00.900
or both or something else?

20
00:01:02.159 --> 00:01:07.230
Yeah, well, thank you. Well. I've always had, uh,

21
00:01:07.419 --> 00:01:12.529
an interest in migration ethics, um, but it was.

22
00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:19.029
My interest really uh developed uh in 2015, 2016,

23
00:01:19.370 --> 00:01:23.129
uh, when there was a so-called refugee crisis with

24
00:01:23.129 --> 00:01:27.089
significant numbers of refugees arriving in Europe and at

25
00:01:27.089 --> 00:01:30.889
the time, um. I was involved in a lot

26
00:01:30.889 --> 00:01:35.190
of charity work trying to support refugees and um.

27
00:01:36.089 --> 00:01:38.930
And that took me to Calais in France, uh,

28
00:01:39.010 --> 00:01:40.730
which is, well, for those of you who don't

29
00:01:40.730 --> 00:01:45.910
know, um. There was an informal refugee settlement in

30
00:01:45.910 --> 00:01:49.569
Calais in northern France, where refugees from different nationalities,

31
00:01:49.819 --> 00:01:55.089
Syria, Sudan, Afghanistan, and so forth, um. They would

32
00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:59.019
Stay in this informal settlement in Calais, uh, attempting

33
00:01:59.019 --> 00:02:01.779
to reach the UK to claim asylum. And I

34
00:02:01.779 --> 00:02:05.650
was a long term, uh, volunteer there, um, in

35
00:02:05.650 --> 00:02:08.339
aid distribution. And then, uh, there was a particular

36
00:02:08.339 --> 00:02:10.889
event that had a really profound impact on me,

37
00:02:11.339 --> 00:02:14.580
which was in, I think February 2016, the French

38
00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:18.699
authorities decided to clear, uh, a portion of the

39
00:02:18.699 --> 00:02:21.919
camp. And so I was there and I witnessed

40
00:02:21.919 --> 00:02:26.529
hundreds of riot police. Enter the camp, uh, rip

41
00:02:26.529 --> 00:02:30.690
refugees from their shelters, um, use violence, beating refugees

42
00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:34.580
with batons, uh, tear gas, water cannon, including against

43
00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:38.089
women and children. I saw one refugee attempt to

44
00:02:38.089 --> 00:02:43.990
commit suicide, um, to, uh, protest against his, his,

45
00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.589
his being arrested, um. And and and it was

46
00:02:47.589 --> 00:02:50.440
a horrendous experience, and in the aftermath of the

47
00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:54.240
event, uh, I think. Around 100 refugee children went

48
00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:57.139
missing. Um, NO one knew where they were, and

49
00:02:57.139 --> 00:03:00.229
so. I was profoundly shocked by what I had

50
00:03:00.229 --> 00:03:05.509
witnessed, um, in 21st century Western Europe, and it

51
00:03:05.509 --> 00:03:09.070
obviously struck me as this is a profoundly unethical,

52
00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:14.130
wrong response for states to adopt in response to,

53
00:03:14.750 --> 00:03:19.050
um, innocent refugees seeking safety. So if this is.

54
00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:21.690
An unethical response, so I wanted to know, well,

55
00:03:21.779 --> 00:03:25.919
what would an ethical response to refugees be, um.

56
00:03:26.809 --> 00:03:29.169
So that's what motivated me to do some research

57
00:03:29.169 --> 00:03:32.369
on this topic, try to understand what an ethical

58
00:03:32.369 --> 00:03:35.520
response would be. And so the book is, um,

59
00:03:35.649 --> 00:03:39.649
the culmination of that effort, that research, uh, where

60
00:03:39.649 --> 00:03:42.550
I seek to develop an understanding of the specific

61
00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:47.529
moral obligations that states have towards refugees and those

62
00:03:47.529 --> 00:03:50.770
obligations form the components of what an ethical response

63
00:03:50.770 --> 00:03:51.369
would be.

64
00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:55.160
No, that it's a very interesting topic and, uh,

65
00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:57.970
I mean, one of the main reasons why I,

66
00:03:58.419 --> 00:04:01.100
uh, wanted to have you on the show was

67
00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:04.119
because I, I think not only it's a very,

68
00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:08.259
uh, I mean, it's something that people have been

69
00:04:08.259 --> 00:04:11.470
dealing with in recent years and even are dealing

70
00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:16.140
now, are dealing with now. Uh, AND, uh, also

71
00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:18.339
because it's a topic that, uh, to be very

72
00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:22.100
honest, I haven't explored before on the show, so

73
00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:24.480
I think it's very important to talk about it.

74
00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:28.160
Uh, I wanted to ask you, what is a

75
00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:32.190
refugee, and I mean, I, I, I imagine that

76
00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:36.600
you will give me the legal or political definition

77
00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:38.920
here, right? So I mean, I, and I think

78
00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:42.760
it's important to clarify for the audience what a

79
00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:49.290
refugee is because Uh, refugee has a different status

80
00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:54.250
than what we could consider a regular migrant, for

81
00:04:54.250 --> 00:04:57.640
example, not only in terms of international law, but

82
00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:02.529
also in terms of how the national law of

83
00:05:02.529 --> 00:05:06.609
each country works and deals with refugees. So what

84
00:05:06.609 --> 00:05:08.149
is the definition?

85
00:05:08.649 --> 00:05:11.040
Oh, good, um, well, you're exactly right. There is

86
00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:15.220
the official definition in international law. Um, WHICH is

87
00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:18.459
a refugee is a person who, owing to a

88
00:05:18.459 --> 00:05:22.660
well-founded fear of persecution for reasons of their race,

89
00:05:22.739 --> 00:05:25.899
their religion, their nationality, the membership of a particular

90
00:05:25.899 --> 00:05:29.820
social group, or their political opinion, is outside the

91
00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:33.739
country of their nationality and because of that fear

92
00:05:33.739 --> 00:05:37.779
of persecution is unwilling to avail themselves of the

93
00:05:37.779 --> 00:05:40.799
protection of that country. So that's the legal definition

94
00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:44.000
as set out in the 1951, um, Geneva Convention

95
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.279
relating to the status of refugee. Now, of course,

96
00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:52.559
a number of philosophers have contested this definition as

97
00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.549
being arbitrarily narrow. One of the primary reasons why

98
00:05:56.549 --> 00:06:00.000
philosophers suggest this definition is arbitrarily narrow is it

99
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.200
seems to have, uh, an undue focus on persecution

100
00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:07.459
in, in particular. So why is it only for

101
00:06:07.459 --> 00:06:11.380
reasons of persecution that we should understand our people

102
00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:13.529
as refugees? So this might not cover, for example,

103
00:06:13.739 --> 00:06:17.619
refugees who are displaced because of war or conflict

104
00:06:17.619 --> 00:06:22.619
or generalized violence or environmental degradation or catastrophe. People

105
00:06:22.619 --> 00:06:25.140
who are forced to flee their country in order

106
00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:27.140
to seek adequate safety elsewhere, but not necessarily because

107
00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:30.380
they've been persecuted on the basis of their identity,

108
00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:35.239
for example, right? So for example, um, Ukrainian refugees.

109
00:06:36.269 --> 00:06:39.260
Might not necessarily be persecuted by it per se.

110
00:06:39.899 --> 00:06:42.470
Rather, they're displaced as a result of war and

111
00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:46.390
conflict and severe threats to their lives, um, and

112
00:06:46.390 --> 00:06:49.170
they're certainly refugees, although they might not necessarily fit

113
00:06:49.429 --> 00:06:56.239
the, uh, conventional definition. So in practice, um. States

114
00:06:56.239 --> 00:06:59.920
will, uh, adhere to a a broader definition and

115
00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:03.619
that's what a lot of philosophers agree with. So,

116
00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:07.299
uh, in the book, I understand the refugee as

117
00:07:07.299 --> 00:07:10.579
a person who has been forcibly displaced, that is

118
00:07:10.839 --> 00:07:14.209
forced to flee their own state of origin. And

119
00:07:14.209 --> 00:07:17.850
is unable to return to it because of severe

120
00:07:17.850 --> 00:07:21.250
threats to their lives, their human rights or their

121
00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:25.049
basic needs, and their own state is unable or

122
00:07:25.049 --> 00:07:29.600
unwilling to adequately protect them from these threats. And

123
00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:34.290
that you're also right to say that. There is

124
00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:37.790
in the law, a distinction between uh refugees and

125
00:07:37.790 --> 00:07:42.559
migrants more broadly. So the key feature of, uh,

126
00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:45.700
a refugee that distinguishes them from migrants more broadly

127
00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:48.220
is the fact that they're forcibly displaced. They are

128
00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:51.619
forced to flee, right? And they're unable to return

129
00:07:51.619 --> 00:07:54.179
to their state of origin because of severe threats

130
00:07:54.179 --> 00:07:57.700
to them. So this might distinguish them from other

131
00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.850
migrants who may not be facing such severe threats,

132
00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:04.779
but who voluntarily migrate for other reasons, um, and

133
00:08:04.779 --> 00:08:08.070
may be able to return. Now, of course. Many

134
00:08:08.070 --> 00:08:10.380
philosophers have said that this is not necessarily a

135
00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:14.540
sharp or clean distinction. And for example, at the

136
00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:18.410
marginal cases, there will be a migrant who's, uh,

137
00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:23.700
leaving severe economic deprivation, uh, severe poverty, uh, in

138
00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:26.820
order to migrate to another state to significantly improve

139
00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:30.190
their material prospects and their quality of life. And

140
00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:34.090
that person's gonna have very strong claims to admission.

141
00:08:35.270 --> 00:08:37.510
um, BUT what I suggest in the book is

142
00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:43.070
that. It's appropriate to have a broad, albeit imperfect

143
00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:46.349
distinction, uh, without denying the claims to admission for

144
00:08:46.349 --> 00:08:50.030
certain migrants. It's important to have a broad distinction

145
00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:52.950
because refugees in being forcibly displaced and unable to

146
00:08:52.950 --> 00:08:56.229
return, uh, will face and will continue to face

147
00:08:56.229 --> 00:08:59.890
very significant harms and injustices in virtue of that

148
00:09:00.549 --> 00:09:04.710
particular circumstance. And also one reason I think it's

149
00:09:04.710 --> 00:09:08.179
important to maintain the imperfect distinction. Is because it

150
00:09:08.179 --> 00:09:11.539
allows us to avoid the debate on immigration more

151
00:09:11.539 --> 00:09:17.900
broadly, because many people will conflate the, uh, which

152
00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:20.380
is a very natural thing to do, the question

153
00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:21.979
of whether states have a right to control their

154
00:09:21.979 --> 00:09:23.900
borders and whether they have a right to control

155
00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:27.900
immigration with the question of obligations towards refugees. But

156
00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:31.659
these are distinct but related questions. One can believe

157
00:09:31.659 --> 00:09:33.299
states have a right to control their borders and

158
00:09:33.299 --> 00:09:36.039
immigration, yet still agree they have obligations. To protect

159
00:09:36.039 --> 00:09:39.760
refugees. So allowing that distinction means we can, we

160
00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:42.559
don't have to settle the debate on immigration. Rather,

161
00:09:42.599 --> 00:09:45.580
we can focus specifically on what obligations states have

162
00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.679
towards refugees, and I think that helps us move

163
00:09:48.679 --> 00:09:53.080
past sometimes often volatile and unproductive public debates about

164
00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:53.780
immigration.

165
00:09:55.270 --> 00:09:57.869
No, yeah, I think it's very important to establish

166
00:09:57.869 --> 00:10:02.270
that distinction for us to or for people to

167
00:10:02.270 --> 00:10:08.869
avoid as much as possible conflating refugees with broader,

168
00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:14.075
broad migrants because, you know, nowadays the far right

169
00:10:14.075 --> 00:10:17.594
and the conservative right many times take advantage of

170
00:10:17.594 --> 00:10:21.474
people's ignorance because, I mean, to be very honest,

171
00:10:21.934 --> 00:10:26.155
I don't think that most people have a proper

172
00:10:26.155 --> 00:10:29.354
understanding of what a refugee is and the distinction

173
00:10:29.354 --> 00:10:32.164
between a refugee and a regular migrant, but then

174
00:10:32.369 --> 00:10:40.210
That contributes to the sort of anti-immigration narratives put

175
00:10:40.210 --> 00:10:43.349
forth by the far right and the conservative right

176
00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:49.440
where they sort of amalgamate refugees with regular migrants

177
00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:52.299
and, and then they point to refugees and say,

178
00:10:52.369 --> 00:10:55.049
oh why are they here we should control our

179
00:10:55.049 --> 00:10:57.765
borders. They have no right to. HERE that they

180
00:10:57.765 --> 00:11:00.755
call themselves refugees, but they are migrants, blah, blah,

181
00:11:00.765 --> 00:11:03.835
blah, you know, that sort of rhetoric and if

182
00:11:03.844 --> 00:11:07.715
when it comes to just regular migrants, uh, the

183
00:11:07.715 --> 00:11:11.094
way we, I mean, many people tend to deal

184
00:11:11.094 --> 00:11:13.405
with them and think about them nowadays is already

185
00:11:13.405 --> 00:11:17.565
inhumane. I mean, it becomes even more severe if

186
00:11:17.565 --> 00:11:20.765
we're talking about refugees, I guess.

187
00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:28.489
Um, INDEED, so I think. There's sometimes in, in,

188
00:11:28.530 --> 00:11:34.609
in the public discourse, um, the. Significant dangers, threats,

189
00:11:34.809 --> 00:11:37.890
harms and justice that refugees are fleeing and have

190
00:11:37.890 --> 00:11:42.169
faced is often lost, and I think focusing again

191
00:11:42.169 --> 00:11:47.950
on um. The actual situation of refugees, um, the

192
00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:52.900
experiences that they face trying to find safety, um,

193
00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:56.669
and the barriers they face in trying to access

194
00:11:56.669 --> 00:12:04.119
protection. And the stories that they have um. Uh,

195
00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:09.780
OFTEN very, uh, upsetting stories, um, and their voices,

196
00:12:09.929 --> 00:12:12.609
uh, just completely lost, um, in this debate, and

197
00:12:12.609 --> 00:12:15.210
I think it's really worthwhile paying close attention to

198
00:12:15.210 --> 00:12:18.130
that because this helps us understand, well, why in

199
00:12:18.130 --> 00:12:23.010
particular we have obligations towards refugees, we, I mean

200
00:12:23.010 --> 00:12:27.330
states in the global north, um. And what precisely

201
00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:29.770
those obligations are, so I think it's really important

202
00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:31.809
to maintain a close focus on that, yeah.

203
00:12:32.489 --> 00:12:38.530
Mhm. Um, WHAT would you say uh characterizes contemporary

204
00:12:38.789 --> 00:12:41.200
refugee movements?

205
00:12:42.940 --> 00:12:45.809
Good. So, uh, I think according to the latest

206
00:12:45.809 --> 00:12:51.179
figures that are available, there's 42.5 million refugees, uh,

207
00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:56.400
worldwide, um, who have been. Forcibly displaced, forced to

208
00:12:56.400 --> 00:13:02.750
flee their own states, um, because of war, conflict,

209
00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:08.219
persecution, uh, widespread generalized violence and extensive human rights

210
00:13:08.219 --> 00:13:14.929
violations, um, to seek adequate safety elsewhere. Now. Having

211
00:13:14.929 --> 00:13:17.969
fled these threats, the vast majority of those refugees

212
00:13:17.969 --> 00:13:20.869
having fled their own states of origin, have not

213
00:13:20.929 --> 00:13:25.080
adequately found that safety. Rather, the vast majority of

214
00:13:25.080 --> 00:13:29.960
refugees. Will live in squalid refugee camps for prolonged

215
00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:33.950
periods of time, or they'll face destitution in urban

216
00:13:33.950 --> 00:13:38.719
areas, um, in low and middle-income countries nearer their

217
00:13:38.719 --> 00:13:42.239
states of origin. Um, AND in these conditions, refugees

218
00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:46.750
will also face, uh, severe poverty, extensive violence, human

219
00:13:46.750 --> 00:13:51.919
rights violations. A small minority, around 10%, um, embark

220
00:13:51.919 --> 00:13:54.770
on perilous journeys to try and reach the, uh,

221
00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:58.159
global North to try and claim asylum. And thousands

222
00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:03.739
will die on their way. And so this is.

223
00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:08.179
Obviously a very serious situation and in my view,

224
00:14:08.239 --> 00:14:13.599
there's two morally significant features of global refugee displacement

225
00:14:13.599 --> 00:14:16.400
which we need to focus on in order to

226
00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:22.719
understand obligations towards them. And one is that. States

227
00:14:22.719 --> 00:14:25.090
in the global north, by which I mean, uh,

228
00:14:25.169 --> 00:14:29.630
the affluent and stable liberal democracies, um, so, uh,

229
00:14:29.690 --> 00:14:33.530
European countries, the UK, Canada, the US, Australia, and

230
00:14:33.530 --> 00:14:34.169
so forth.

231
00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:34.929
Japan

232
00:14:36.330 --> 00:14:41.599
indeed, yes, uh, so. One important feature of global

233
00:14:41.599 --> 00:14:44.750
refugee displacement is that these countries, these global north

234
00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:49.840
countries are not necessarily mere innocent bystanders overlooking these

235
00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:53.640
harms that are occurring to refugees, um, but rather

236
00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:57.280
they adopt a variety of policies and practices in

237
00:14:57.280 --> 00:14:59.270
response to those refugees trying to seek safety on

238
00:14:59.270 --> 00:15:04.700
their territories. Practices such as border violence, detention, uh,

239
00:15:04.760 --> 00:15:07.830
forced encampment. And forced containment, which I can go

240
00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:10.609
into more detail later on if you wish, um,

241
00:15:11.159 --> 00:15:14.119
which result in significant harms and human rights violations

242
00:15:14.119 --> 00:15:17.400
for refugees. And I think understanding that feature of

243
00:15:17.400 --> 00:15:21.159
global refugee displacement is really important to understanding states'

244
00:15:21.159 --> 00:15:24.599
negative obligations towards refugees, and I can explain what

245
00:15:24.599 --> 00:15:27.119
I mean by negative obligations later on if you

246
