491
00:30:42.229 --> 00:30:44.699
in conditions where torture will occur to them. These

492
00:30:44.699 --> 00:30:47.069
are negative duties not to harm or violate the

493
00:30:47.069 --> 00:30:51.319
rights of others. Now negative duties are taken to

494
00:30:51.319 --> 00:30:55.119
be particularly strong duties, perhaps the most fundamental moral

495
00:30:55.119 --> 00:30:57.880
duties that we all have. Our duty is not

496
00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:03.780
to harm others. Now positive duties. Or obligations are

497
00:31:03.780 --> 00:31:09.250
duties to perform an act that would benefit or

498
00:31:09.250 --> 00:31:13.619
otherwise assist, uh, another person. So for example, you

499
00:31:13.619 --> 00:31:16.540
may have a positive duty to save someone from

500
00:31:16.540 --> 00:31:18.739
being tortured if you could simply warn them, for

501
00:31:18.739 --> 00:31:21.599
example, right? And it would be morally wrong to

502
00:31:22.209 --> 00:31:23.739
let them be tortured if you could save them

503
00:31:23.739 --> 00:31:29.849
at a little cost to yourself. Now, Negative duties

504
00:31:29.849 --> 00:31:32.650
are primarily understood to be particularly strong duties and

505
00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:35.770
stronger than one's, uh, positive duties. That's not to

506
00:31:35.770 --> 00:31:38.510
say that one's positive duties are weak, but that

507
00:31:38.569 --> 00:31:40.920
all else being equal, one has a stronger negative

508
00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:44.209
duty not to subject someone to harm, uh, compared

509
00:31:44.209 --> 00:31:46.729
to one's positive duty to save them from comparable

510
00:31:46.729 --> 00:31:51.770
harm. And so these duties are grounded in what

511
00:31:51.770 --> 00:31:56.099
I call basic normative commitments, that is. They are

512
00:31:56.099 --> 00:32:00.780
endorsed by all plausible normative ethical theories. They're endorsed

513
00:32:00.780 --> 00:32:04.339
by the ethical tenets of all, um, ethical religious

514
00:32:04.339 --> 00:32:09.680
doctrines, and they're widely accepted in common morality across,

515
00:32:09.780 --> 00:32:13.800
uh, an overlapping consensus of reasonable comprehensive doctrines, so.

516
00:32:14.719 --> 00:32:18.839
Nearly everyone agrees that we have these obligations, these

517
00:32:18.839 --> 00:32:21.900
moral obligations. And so I'm trying to draw on

518
00:32:21.900 --> 00:32:26.880
these core common moral commitments, um, to understand states'

519
00:32:27.060 --> 00:32:29.900
negative and positive duties towards refugees. Now, I think

520
00:32:29.900 --> 00:32:34.020
this is important, this distinction, because most of the

521
00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:37.140
philosophical literature has focused only on the positive duties

522
00:32:37.140 --> 00:32:40.819
to protect refugees. What positive obligations the states have

523
00:32:40.819 --> 00:32:43.500
to perform an act to help refugees. And there

524
00:32:43.500 --> 00:32:48.560
hasn't been sufficient attention focused on the negative obligations

525
00:32:48.579 --> 00:32:51.650
of states not to harm or violate the rights

526
00:32:51.650 --> 00:32:54.119
of refugees. So I think an account of this

527
00:32:54.119 --> 00:32:56.540
has been missing in the philosophical literature and it's

528
00:32:56.540 --> 00:33:00.599
very, very important. And the distinction is also important

529
00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:04.420
because focusing on the positive duties we, as we

530
00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:08.260
saw earlier, there's a lot of disagreement about, well,

531
00:33:08.349 --> 00:33:12.839
what precisely are the positive obligations, right? And so,

532
00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:15.569
um. As I suggest in the book, we need

533
00:33:15.569 --> 00:33:18.050
to focus on the situation of refugees, and that's

534
00:33:18.050 --> 00:33:21.170
a way in which you can more properly understand

535
00:33:21.170 --> 00:33:23.089
the positive duties. And the thought is we need

536
00:33:23.089 --> 00:33:25.719
an account of both the negative and the positive

537
00:33:25.719 --> 00:33:29.270
duties, uh, of states towards refugees if we want

538
00:33:29.270 --> 00:33:32.930
a full account of state's obligations towards refugees.

539
00:33:34.420 --> 00:33:39.869
So what kinds of state practices are used, or

540
00:33:39.869 --> 00:33:43.949
at least which are the more commonly used in

541
00:33:43.949 --> 00:33:47.800
response to refugees, and which of them do you

542
00:33:47.800 --> 00:33:51.189
think can be or should be classified as either

543
00:33:51.189 --> 00:33:55.079
doing or allowing harm? And I mean in this

544
00:33:55.079 --> 00:34:00.670
particular case of dealing with refugees, what counts as

545
00:34:00.670 --> 00:34:01.150
harm?

546
00:34:02.579 --> 00:34:08.719
OK, good. So So I appeal to the doctrine

547
00:34:08.719 --> 00:34:12.929
of doing and allowing harm, um. Which to explain

548
00:34:12.929 --> 00:34:20.179
is uh. The principle that It's morally worse and

549
00:34:20.179 --> 00:34:23.050
requires a higher level of justification to do harm

550
00:34:23.050 --> 00:34:25.208
rather than fail to aid and simply allow harm

551
00:34:25.208 --> 00:34:27.989
to someone. So this maps onto the distinction between

552
00:34:27.989 --> 00:34:31.149
negative and positive duties. One has stronger negative duties

553
00:34:31.370 --> 00:34:34.929
not to torture a person oneself compared to one's

554
00:34:34.929 --> 00:34:38.770
positive duties to save someone from torture, right? And

555
00:34:38.770 --> 00:34:41.879
so I employ this distinction which is widely accepted

556
00:34:41.879 --> 00:34:45.010
in common morality owing to the widely accepted robust

557
00:34:45.010 --> 00:34:48.520
moral constraint against harming people. Uh, I appealed to

558
00:34:48.520 --> 00:34:53.360
this. To draw attention to certain practices and try

559
00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:56.469
and classify them as doing or allowing harm. And

560
00:34:56.469 --> 00:35:00.620
if these practices are doing harm. Then states that

561
00:35:00.620 --> 00:35:04.780
employ them are not mere innocent bystanders disconnected from

562
00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:09.459
the harms refugees, but are actively harming innocent refugees

563
00:35:09.459 --> 00:35:14.090
looking for safety. And if that's true, then they

564
00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:18.409
will have urgent negative duties to refrain from unjustly

565
00:35:18.409 --> 00:35:21.649
harming those refugees and or rectify the harm caused.

566
00:35:21.729 --> 00:35:24.409
So a lot matters on whether these practices are

567
00:35:24.409 --> 00:35:26.370
in fact doing and allowing harm. So then I

568
00:35:26.370 --> 00:35:30.350
look at certain practices. In the book, uh, and

569
00:35:30.350 --> 00:35:33.120
classify them as either doing and allowing harm. Now

570
00:35:33.120 --> 00:35:37.520
some practices I look at include border violence. So

571
00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:41.800
for example, um, the UK has invested millions in

572
00:35:41.800 --> 00:35:45.600
supporting the CRS riot police in France who are

573
00:35:45.600 --> 00:35:48.600
reported to engage in violence against refugees, beaten with

574
00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:52.870
batons, often during evictions of camps. Also tactics of

575
00:35:52.870 --> 00:35:56.969
intimidation, harassment, confiscation of personal property, and so forth.

576
00:35:57.989 --> 00:36:00.709
And to take another example, on the Hungarian border

577
00:36:00.709 --> 00:36:03.790
with Serbia, there's been reports of violent pushbacks of

578
00:36:03.790 --> 00:36:07.209
refugees, refugees being beaten for hours on end, causing

579
00:36:07.209 --> 00:36:10.070
life changing injuries and so forth. And these are

580
00:36:10.070 --> 00:36:14.510
just two examples of a wider trend of violence,

581
00:36:14.669 --> 00:36:19.949
pushbacks, crackdowns of refugees at many European state borders,

582
00:36:20.149 --> 00:36:22.510
including Greece and Italy and so forth, as well

583
00:36:22.510 --> 00:36:28.139
as the US-Mexico border. Now border violence is straightforwardly

584
00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:35.060
doing harm to refugees, um. It causes them, um,

585
00:36:35.219 --> 00:36:38.620
to occupy a level of well-being that's far lower

586
00:36:38.620 --> 00:36:39.979
than it would have been in the nearest possible

587
00:36:39.979 --> 00:36:43.340
world in which they weren't subjected to these tactics

588
00:36:43.340 --> 00:36:47.459
of violence and so forth. So that's one practice.

589
00:36:47.699 --> 00:36:53.129
Uh, ANOTHER practice is detention. So, for example. Um,

590
00:36:53.219 --> 00:36:57.919
IN an arrangement between, um, Italy and other EU

591
00:36:57.919 --> 00:37:00.340
states on the one hand and Libya on the

592
00:37:00.340 --> 00:37:04.580
other hand, um. Refugees who are trying to make

593
00:37:04.580 --> 00:37:07.919
that crossing across the Mediterranean Sea from North Africa

594
00:37:08.179 --> 00:37:13.929
to Italy are intercepted and returned to be placed

595
00:37:13.929 --> 00:37:16.889
in detention centers on the Libyan coast as well

596
00:37:16.889 --> 00:37:19.969
as in the Libyan mainland, and in these detention

597
00:37:19.969 --> 00:37:25.280
centers, refugees face overcrowding, disease, starvation, as well as,

598
00:37:25.729 --> 00:37:29.189
um, human rights abuses from the Libyan authorities, including

599
00:37:29.489 --> 00:37:33.229
uh rape and sexual violence, torture, even being traded

600
00:37:33.229 --> 00:37:39.060
as slaves. Now of course, detention again is. A

601
00:37:39.060 --> 00:37:41.860
practice that harms these refugees, it causes them to

602
00:37:41.860 --> 00:37:45.360
be much worse off, uh, much worse off, sorry,

603
00:37:45.699 --> 00:37:49.260
in aspects of their well-being, their mental and physical

604
00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:51.580
health, their freedom, their human rights, than they would

605
00:37:51.580 --> 00:37:53.260
have been in the nearest possible world in which

606
00:37:53.260 --> 00:37:55.530
they were not placed in these detention centers. So

607
00:37:55.530 --> 00:38:00.100
that straightforwardly harms them. Another practice is, uh, sorry,

608
00:38:00.260 --> 00:38:04.879
uh, encampment. Um, SO for example, Uh, as part

609
00:38:04.879 --> 00:38:09.149
of the EU-Turkey deal, uh, initiated in 2016, uh,

610
00:38:09.199 --> 00:38:12.159
refugees who had made the crossing across the Aegean

611
00:38:12.159 --> 00:38:15.000
Sea from Turkey to Greece and arrived on those

612
00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:19.760
Greek islands, um, were forcibly enclosed into camps and

613
00:38:19.760 --> 00:38:23.260
denied onward movement to the Greek mainland and to,

614
00:38:23.389 --> 00:38:27.649
uh, the European mainland. And, um, they're made to

615
00:38:27.649 --> 00:38:29.449
stay in these camps and there was a lack

616
00:38:29.449 --> 00:38:34.209
of adequate sanitation and, um, subsistence support and also

617
00:38:34.209 --> 00:38:37.530
extensive human rights violations within these camp settings. Uh,

618
00:38:37.610 --> 00:38:39.290
MANY of them have since been closed and replaced

619
00:38:39.290 --> 00:38:43.729
with these controlled access centers which similarly deny refugees

620
00:38:43.729 --> 00:38:46.169
free movement and so forth, and there's all reports

621
00:38:46.169 --> 00:38:49.090
for, uh, concerning human rights abuses in these centers

622
00:38:49.090 --> 00:38:53.989
as well. So this similar detention is harmful to

623
00:38:53.989 --> 00:38:58.120
refugees, uh, insofar as it makes them much worse

624
00:38:58.120 --> 00:38:59.399
off than they would have been had they not

625
00:38:59.399 --> 00:39:02.620
been forced into these camps. Um, AND then the

626
00:39:02.620 --> 00:39:06.260
final practice that I consider, which is not exhaustive

627
00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:08.550
of all the practice, by the way, um, but,

628
00:39:08.659 --> 00:39:11.100
uh, one important practice to consider is the practice

629
00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:17.370
of containment. Now containment, um. Containment policies are exactly

630
00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:20.810
that, they are policies initiated by states that seek

631
00:39:20.810 --> 00:39:25.679
to contain refugees away from the state's territory. In

632
00:39:25.679 --> 00:39:30.850
regions closer to refugee states of origin. Um, BUT

633
00:39:30.850 --> 00:39:33.370
the direct result of these containment policies is that

634
00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:37.010
refugees are contained in certain regions. Where they face

635
00:39:37.010 --> 00:39:40.330
extreme poverty, uh, severe threats to their lives and

636
00:39:40.330 --> 00:39:44.110
freedoms, and extensive human rights violations. So, for example,

637
00:39:44.550 --> 00:39:48.969
that arrangement with Libya, um, blocks that migratory route

638
00:39:48.969 --> 00:39:53.810
to seek safety in, in, in Europe and. Thereby

639
00:39:53.810 --> 00:39:57.280
contains refugees in Libya and other regions in North

640
00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:00.889
Africa, where they face immense, uh, extensive human rights

641
00:40:00.889 --> 00:40:03.830
abuses and so forth. And that EU Turkey deal

642
00:40:04.449 --> 00:40:07.760
blocks that migratory route from Turkey to Greece and

643
00:40:07.760 --> 00:40:10.959
in doing so, contains refugees in regions closer to

644
00:40:10.959 --> 00:40:14.610
their states of origin in Turkey, Jordan and Lebanon

645
00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:20.389
where they face, um, severe harms, uh. Poverty, extreme

646
00:40:20.389 --> 00:40:23.709
human rights abuses, especially for those refugees right now,

647
00:40:24.030 --> 00:40:27.429
um, in Lebanon who, uh, are facing increased risks

648
00:40:27.429 --> 00:40:29.489
as a, as a result of the conflict there.

649
00:40:30.570 --> 00:40:34.320
And so these policies of containment. Um, THEY'RE quite

650
00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:37.439
difficult to classify. So I spent some time in

651
00:40:37.439 --> 00:40:41.340
the book trying to classify whether containment is doing

652
00:40:41.479 --> 00:40:44.719
or allowing harm to refugees. And I, and I

653
00:40:44.719 --> 00:40:47.320
can explain if you wish, my conclusion there.

654
00:40:47.679 --> 00:40:50.219
No, yes, please, please do so. Yeah.

655
00:40:50.679 --> 00:40:55.399
OK, so what I suggest is that containment should

656
00:40:55.399 --> 00:40:57.959
be understood as what I call a denial of

657
00:40:57.959 --> 00:41:02.110
escape case. Now, a denial of escape case is

658
00:41:02.110 --> 00:41:06.010
where. There's a potentially harmful sequence of events that's

659
00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:09.610
threatening a person, but there's a pre-existing means for

660
00:41:09.610 --> 00:41:12.350
that person to simply escape that threat of harm,

661
00:41:13.090 --> 00:41:16.590
um. But what happens is then an agent acts

662
00:41:16.590 --> 00:41:19.709
to place an obstacle in the way, which prevents

663
00:41:19.709 --> 00:41:23.719
the victim from escaping the harm. Such that the

664
00:41:23.719 --> 00:41:27.959
victim is in fact harmed, um, by that sequence

665
00:41:27.959 --> 00:41:30.810
of events. So for example, if there was uh

666
00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:34.780
a person. Um, WHO was on some train tracks

667
00:41:34.780 --> 00:41:36.620
through no fault of their own, and there was

668
00:41:36.620 --> 00:41:38.500
a train coming towards them, but they could simply

669
00:41:38.500 --> 00:41:40.739
step aside and let the train go by so

670
00:41:40.739 --> 00:41:42.699
they could escape the threat of harm, but then

671
00:41:42.699 --> 00:41:46.379
you act to tie them to the tracks such

672
00:41:46.379 --> 00:41:49.479
that they cannot escape. Um, SUCH that they are

673
00:41:49.479 --> 00:41:53.229
then harmed, then. That's a denial of escape case,

674
00:41:53.250 --> 00:41:55.709
and I suggest denial of escape cases like that

675
00:41:56.050 --> 00:41:59.250
are, uh, doing harm. They count as doing harm.

676
00:41:59.429 --> 00:42:02.810
So, and I think containment is a denial of

677
00:42:02.810 --> 00:42:06.330
escape case. Refugees are in harm's way. They're facing

678
00:42:06.330 --> 00:42:10.719
human rights abuses, um, uh, severe threats to their

679
00:42:10.719 --> 00:42:14.570
lives and freedoms, extreme poverty and whatever, um, but

680
00:42:14.570 --> 00:42:18.550
fortunately, there's, uh, a pre-existing means of escape. They

681
00:42:18.889 --> 00:42:22.379
are. They can claim asylum and seek safety in

682
00:42:22.379 --> 00:42:24.979
northern states territories, as is their human right. By

683
00:42:24.979 --> 00:42:27.050
the way, Article 14 of the Universal Declaration of

684
00:42:27.050 --> 00:42:29.620
Human Rights, they have the right to seek and

685
00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:33.330
claim asylum. Mhm. Um, BUT then what these states

686
00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:37.090
do is they perform an act to introduce a

687
00:42:37.090 --> 00:42:41.350
containment policy, right, which blocks that means of escape.

688
00:42:42.209 --> 00:42:44.290
Such that they are no longer able to escape

689
00:42:44.290 --> 00:42:48.120
those harms, such that they then endure those harms.

690
00:42:48.449 --> 00:42:51.370
So it'd be the equivalent of, say, well, it

691
00:42:51.370 --> 00:42:53.010
wouldn't necessarily be the equivalent, but another denial of

692
00:42:53.010 --> 00:42:56.360
escape case would be, for example, um, blocking the

693
00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:58.969
fire exit to a burning building such that people

694
00:42:58.969 --> 00:43:02.550
cannot escape, and that I suggest constitutes doing harm.

695
00:43:03.139 --> 00:43:06.149
So I think if we understand containment. As a

696
00:43:06.149 --> 00:43:08.300
denial of escape case, which I think it is,

697
00:43:08.669 --> 00:43:12.110
then this yields the conclusion that it constitutes doing

698
00:43:12.110 --> 00:43:16.090
harm. So states that uh initiate containment policies are,

699
00:43:16.389 --> 00:43:20.199
are doing harm and then I think an interesting

700
00:43:20.219 --> 00:43:24.530
implication follows from this. Uh, SO at the top

701
00:43:24.530 --> 00:43:27.050
of the interview, we were talking about whether some

702
00:43:27.050 --> 00:43:30.850
of these practices like containment are illegal, and currently

703
00:43:30.850 --> 00:43:35.530
containment is not illegal under international refugee law. But,

704
00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:39.600
uh, refoulement is illegal under the international refugee law.

705
00:43:39.679 --> 00:43:42.879
So that is the practice of, so the principle

706
00:43:42.879 --> 00:43:45.639
of non-refoulement holds that if a refugee arrives in

707
00:43:45.639 --> 00:43:49.530
your territory. You may not return that refugee to

708
00:43:49.530 --> 00:43:52.010
any territory where their life, freedom, or human rights

709
00:43:52.010 --> 00:43:54.560
would be under threat. So that is a principle

710
00:43:54.560 --> 00:43:57.830
of international law, uh, it's widely adhered to, uh,

711
00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:06.030
among states, um. Now violating non-refoulement, that is um.

712
00:44:07.340 --> 00:44:10.489
Returning a refugee to a situation. In which harms

713
00:44:10.489 --> 00:44:13.290
may occur to them does not necessarily cause the

714
00:44:13.290 --> 00:44:17.689
harms or the harmful circumstances, but place refugees in

715
00:44:17.689 --> 00:44:21.909
those circumstances. So refoulement would be the equivalent of

716
00:44:22.610 --> 00:44:25.889
returning, um, so throwing an innocent child who had

717
00:44:25.889 --> 00:44:28.229
escaped onto your dry land back into a pond

718
00:44:28.610 --> 00:44:31.110
where they may drown. That's what refoulement would be.

719
00:44:31.449 --> 00:44:34.570
And it's widely agreed that this would be morally

720
00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:38.060
unthinkable and it's prohibited in international refugee law. But

721
00:44:38.060 --> 00:44:44.830
now consider containment, which uh concerns. Containing refugees away

722
00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:47.550
from one's territory in regions where they face severe

723
00:44:47.550 --> 00:44:50.469
threats to their lives, human rights and basic needs.

724
00:44:51.070 --> 00:44:54.260
Now this would be the equivalent of holding an

725
00:44:54.260 --> 00:44:57.750
innocent child at arm's length, uh, in a, in

726
00:44:57.750 --> 00:45:01.189
a pond where they may drown, uh, preventing them

727
00:45:01.189 --> 00:45:04.270
from swimming to safety onto one's dry land. So

728
00:45:04.270 --> 00:45:05.969
it's holding them at arm's length such that they

729
00:45:06.229 --> 00:45:09.209
will face this harm. Now what I suggest in

730
00:45:09.209 --> 00:45:11.540
the book is that there's no more difference between

731
00:45:11.540 --> 00:45:13.850
these acts. There's no moral difference between throwing an

732
00:45:13.850 --> 00:45:16.260
innocent child back into the pond where they may

733
00:45:16.260 --> 00:45:19.379
drown and holding an innocent child at arm's length

734
00:45:19.379 --> 00:45:21.100
in the pond where they may drown, preventing them

735
00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:24.449
from swimming to safety onto your dry land. And

736
