01:00:02.610 --> 01:00:06.199
accurate. Uh, THEN we see that states who enact

978
01:00:06.199 --> 01:00:10.459
these harmful policies are acting wrongfully and have urgent,

979
01:00:10.469 --> 01:00:14.750
compulsory negative moral duties to refrain from these unjust

980
01:00:14.750 --> 01:00:17.989
policies and rectify the harms caused. So, I think

981
01:00:17.989 --> 01:00:21.439
it matters greatly whether, um, these are direct obstructural

982
01:00:21.439 --> 01:00:23.790
injustices, and I think there's good reason to think

983
01:00:23.790 --> 01:00:27.129
that they are, in fact, direct injustices against refugees.

984
01:00:28.739 --> 01:00:33.540
So what are then the positive duties of states

985
01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:35.340
toward refugees?

986
01:00:36.520 --> 01:00:43.120
OK, so, So that was the first half of

987
01:00:43.120 --> 01:00:44.840
my book, as it were. So focusing on the

988
01:00:44.840 --> 01:00:49.139
negative duties of, uh, refugees, where I've argued that.

989
01:00:49.800 --> 01:00:51.360
Certain states in the global North are not innocent

990
01:00:51.360 --> 01:00:56.179
bystanders, um, they adopt practices that harm refugees. These

991
01:00:56.709 --> 01:00:59.000
practices are not justified, and this is a direct

992
01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:02.550
injustice. Um, SO this grounds strong negative duties of

993
01:01:02.550 --> 01:01:05.550
states to reform current practices. But what about, as

994
01:01:05.550 --> 01:01:09.820
you said, these, um, these positive duties. Uh, POSITIVE

995
01:01:09.820 --> 01:01:12.149
duties to provide a benefit or otherwise assist or

996
01:01:12.149 --> 01:01:15.340
protect refugees. I suggest again if we focus on

997
01:01:15.340 --> 01:01:20.300
the situation of refugees, um, this helps us to

998
01:01:20.300 --> 01:01:24.040
understand the nature, weight, and specification of positive duties

999
01:01:24.459 --> 01:01:27.300
towards them. So if we look at the situation

1000
01:01:27.300 --> 01:01:34.889
of refugees. We see that, well, Most refugees come

1001
01:01:34.889 --> 01:01:39.409
from um. Are fleeing severe human rights violations in

1002
01:01:39.409 --> 01:01:41.830
their states of origin as a result of war,

1003
01:01:42.010 --> 01:01:44.610
conflicts and persecution or whatever it might be. So

1004
01:01:44.610 --> 01:01:50.260
this includes targeted bombing of civilian areas, um, Um,

1005
01:01:50.510 --> 01:01:55.590
generalized violence, cruel and degrading treatment, torture, sexual and

1006
01:01:55.590 --> 01:02:01.810
gender-based violence, ethnic cleansing, uh, forced disappearances, extrajudicial killings,

1007
01:02:02.229 --> 01:02:07.149
um. And potential genocide. So these are the causes

1008
01:02:07.570 --> 01:02:09.929
of refugee displacement. This is why refugees are fleeing

1009
01:02:09.929 --> 01:02:12.830
their states of origin. Uh, AND that's true in,

1010
01:02:13.129 --> 01:02:16.810
um, for example, the, the six states that produce

1011
01:02:16.810 --> 01:02:21.840
the most refugees, um, Ukraine, Afghanistan, Syria, uh, Sudan,

1012
01:02:21.949 --> 01:02:26.290
Venezuela, South Sudan. Uh, SO they're, they're facing human

1013
01:02:26.290 --> 01:02:27.969
rights violations in their states of origin. That's why

1014
01:02:27.969 --> 01:02:33.060
they've fled. And then once they've left their states

1015
01:02:33.060 --> 01:02:36.219
of origin, again, they haven't necessarily found safety, but

1016
01:02:36.219 --> 01:02:40.179
rather they'll either reside in refugee camps for prolonged

1017
01:02:40.179 --> 01:02:41.489
periods of time. This is true for the vast

1018
01:02:41.489 --> 01:02:44.280
majority of, of, of refugees. They'll either face a

1019
01:02:44.280 --> 01:02:46.360
life in refugee camps for prolonged periods of time

1020
01:02:46.659 --> 01:02:49.260
or a life in urban areas where they'll have

1021
01:02:49.260 --> 01:02:53.379
a sub-citizen status. They won't be granted equality before

1022
01:02:53.379 --> 01:02:56.219
the law, so they'll be subjected to. Additional human

1023
01:02:56.219 --> 01:03:00.060
rights violations without protection or recourse to the, the

1024
01:03:00.060 --> 01:03:03.340
law, or they'll risk their lives on dangerous journeys

1025
01:03:03.340 --> 01:03:05.139
to try and reach the global North, in which

1026
01:03:05.139 --> 01:03:09.120
case, again, they're vulnerable to significant human rights violations

1027
01:03:09.300 --> 01:03:15.020
from traffickers, from border officials, and so forth. So

1028
01:03:15.020 --> 01:03:17.300
refugees are also facing these human rights violations whilst

1029
01:03:17.300 --> 01:03:22.429
they're displaced, either in camps. Or urban areas or

1030
01:03:22.489 --> 01:03:26.250
um on journeys and this is important for understanding

1031
01:03:26.250 --> 01:03:30.560
obligations towards them because. The violations that refugees are

1032
01:03:30.560 --> 01:03:36.679
subjected to. In virtue of their displacement involve significant

1033
01:03:36.679 --> 01:03:39.580
additional harms that I think are often not sufficiently

1034
01:03:39.580 --> 01:03:43.239
recognized. So it's not merely the case that refugees

1035
01:03:43.310 --> 01:03:47.540
are severely like physically suffering and have certain biological

1036
01:03:47.540 --> 01:03:50.100
needs of food, water, shelter, and so forth, but

1037
01:03:50.100 --> 01:03:52.379
additionally, they're facing these harms as a result of

1038
01:03:52.379 --> 01:03:55.699
these violations which include a violation of their autonomy.

1039
01:03:55.780 --> 01:03:59.600
Their control over their life has been completely disrupted,

1040
01:03:59.699 --> 01:04:04.169
um. And they have very little opportunities to live

1041
01:04:04.169 --> 01:04:06.050
their lives or rebuild their lives according to their

1042
01:04:06.050 --> 01:04:08.919
own wishes. And they don't have much control over

1043
01:04:08.919 --> 01:04:11.320
their own environment or their existence or, or anything

1044
01:04:11.320 --> 01:04:13.919
like that. So this violation of autonomy is, is

1045
01:04:13.919 --> 01:04:16.800
profound. They also endure a violation of, uh, a

1046
01:04:16.800 --> 01:04:21.959
dignified existence, uh, of their dignity insofar as. They're

1047
01:04:21.959 --> 01:04:26.000
often forced to endure conditions and treatment which are

1048
01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.780
below acceptable standards for a dignified existence. Think of,

1049
01:04:29.080 --> 01:04:33.000
um, squalid refugee camps, for example, or facing extreme

1050
01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:36.320
destitution in urban areas without any sort of protection

1051
01:04:36.320 --> 01:04:40.199
from the local authorities and so forth. They also

1052
01:04:40.199 --> 01:04:43.760
endure a violation of their moral worth or, uh,

1053
01:04:43.800 --> 01:04:45.280
you might describe this as a violation of their

1054
01:04:45.280 --> 01:04:49.959
humanity insofar as they're not viewed and treated as

1055
01:04:49.959 --> 01:04:53.500
equal human beings with equal moral worth, but rather,

1056
01:04:53.739 --> 01:04:58.310
they're viewed and treated as less, as subhuman, as

1057
01:04:58.310 --> 01:05:00.699
having inferior moral worth. And that would be true.

1058
01:05:01.570 --> 01:05:05.969
In the violations they're subjected to, the people subjecting

1059
01:05:05.969 --> 01:05:08.209
them to this treatment will be treating them as

1060
01:05:08.209 --> 01:05:10.530
inferior, but also it's true, as we can see

1061
01:05:10.530 --> 01:05:15.290
in various media representations, um, or representations by the

1062
01:05:15.290 --> 01:05:16.840
political class and states in the global North that

1063
01:05:16.840 --> 01:05:21.550
refugees aren't, um, recognized necessarily as equal human beings,

1064
01:05:21.810 --> 01:05:24.409
but rather that they're viewed and treated as something

1065
01:05:24.409 --> 01:05:28.739
less. So these, these harms are very significant, and

1066
01:05:28.739 --> 01:05:35.120
I think they're, um. Relevant to understanding obligations towards

1067
01:05:35.120 --> 01:05:41.709
them. Um And then there's also another important phenomenon

1068
01:05:41.810 --> 01:05:46.600
that refugees endure whilst they're displaced. Um, WHICH is

1069
01:05:46.600 --> 01:05:51.060
one that Hannah Arendt identified, and it's the phenomenon

1070
01:05:51.060 --> 01:05:59.530
of rightlessness. Which entails that. Well, refugees may have

1071
01:05:59.530 --> 01:06:03.209
human rights on paper, right, because all human beings

1072
01:06:03.209 --> 01:06:08.030
have equal human rights, um, but they are subjected

1073
01:06:08.169 --> 01:06:11.689
to abuses and violence regardless, as if they had

1074
01:06:11.689 --> 01:06:14.459
no human rights whatsoever, right? So in this sense,

1075
01:06:14.530 --> 01:06:18.129
they are rightless, uh, as Hannah Arendt identified, which

1076
01:06:18.129 --> 01:06:22.040
I understand as. They lack the capabilities to enjoy

1077
01:06:22.040 --> 01:06:24.479
the content of their human rights. So, though they

1078
01:06:24.479 --> 01:06:27.639
may have a right against torture, for example, on

1079
01:06:27.639 --> 01:06:32.110
paper. Uh, THEY lack the substantive right because they

1080
01:06:32.110 --> 01:06:35.469
do not have the capabilities to enjoy that human

1081
01:06:35.469 --> 01:06:37.510
right against torture because they can be subjected to

1082
01:06:37.510 --> 01:06:42.780
that rights violation regardless. So, one way of trying

1083
01:06:42.780 --> 01:06:44.820
to understand this phenomenon of rightlessness is like to

1084
01:06:44.820 --> 01:06:47.669
imagine you're um like a citizen of the UK.

1085
01:06:49.469 --> 01:06:52.149
And then you consider your rights, your human right

1086
01:06:52.149 --> 01:06:55.229
against cruel and degrading treatment, for example. Now, you

1087
01:06:55.229 --> 01:06:57.629
would probably barely even need to think about this

1088
01:06:57.629 --> 01:07:00.050
right against cruel and degrading treatment because there's a,

1089
01:07:00.350 --> 01:07:03.149
a vast infrastructure in place in the UK that

1090
01:07:03.149 --> 01:07:08.219
protects your right. Uh, THERE'S, uh, enforcement mechanisms, there's,

1091
01:07:08.350 --> 01:07:13.949
uh, laws, there's police, there's these, um. There's vast

1092
01:07:13.949 --> 01:07:16.350
infrastructure in place as well as an economic system

1093
01:07:16.350 --> 01:07:19.310
in place to facilitate this protection mechanism, such that

1094
01:07:19.310 --> 01:07:21.949
you can go through your life never even worrying

1095
01:07:21.949 --> 01:07:25.909
about your right against cruel and degrading treatment. But

1096
01:07:25.909 --> 01:07:28.510
then suppose that the UK descends into a civil

1097
01:07:28.510 --> 01:07:33.100
war, uh, the government collapses, there's extensive violence everywhere,

1098
01:07:33.110 --> 01:07:35.389
and then you have to flee the UK and

1099
01:07:35.389 --> 01:07:38.189
so you make it across the Channel on a

1100
01:07:38.189 --> 01:07:41.209
small boat to France to try and claim asylum.

1101
01:07:42.040 --> 01:07:45.300
Um, And you end up in a refugee camp

1102
01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:49.889
with lots of other, um, British refugees. And then

1103
01:07:53.139 --> 01:07:56.479
Imagine now your human right against cruel and degrading

1104
01:07:56.479 --> 01:07:58.860
treatment if someone tries to threaten your right. Now

1105
01:07:58.860 --> 01:08:01.850
that that infrastructure is not in place anymore. There's

1106
01:08:01.850 --> 01:08:03.739
no one you can turn to, there's no British

1107
01:08:03.739 --> 01:08:05.520
government who's going to try and protect your right.

1108
01:08:06.100 --> 01:08:07.770
So if someone threatens your right, whether that be

1109
01:08:07.770 --> 01:08:10.500
a border official, a trafficker or something like that.

1110
01:08:11.489 --> 01:08:14.570
Your right very likely will be violated and in

1111
01:08:14.570 --> 01:08:16.779
this sense, you don't really have the right against

1112
01:08:16.779 --> 01:08:19.129
cruel and degrading treatment because you're going to be

1113
01:08:19.129 --> 01:08:21.560
subjected to that abuse regardless and there's no one

1114
01:08:21.560 --> 01:08:24.459
you can turn to. So, this is a phenomenon

1115
01:08:24.459 --> 01:08:27.729
that refugees face, and I think that's also really

1116
01:08:27.729 --> 01:08:31.419
important to understanding obligations towards them. And so, looking

1117
01:08:31.419 --> 01:08:33.779
at this situation, the harms that refugees face as

1118
01:08:33.779 --> 01:08:37.020
a result of the violations and their rightlessness means

1119
01:08:37.020 --> 01:08:41.839
that positive duties towards them. Shouldn't merely be to

1120
01:08:41.839 --> 01:08:45.549
alleviate any physical harms, but need to address this

1121
01:08:45.549 --> 01:08:49.279
violation of autonomy by providing opportunities for refugees to

1122
01:08:49.279 --> 01:08:52.680
have an autonomous existence, um, to rebuild their lives

1123
01:08:52.680 --> 01:08:55.680
according to their own wishes. It needs to respond

1124
01:08:55.680 --> 01:08:58.479
to the harm to dignity by providing opportunities for

1125
01:08:58.479 --> 01:09:01.479
refugees to have a dignified existence away from the

1126
01:09:01.479 --> 01:09:04.720
squalor of certain, uh, refugee camps, for example, that

1127
01:09:04.720 --> 01:09:08.770
have a decent standard of living, um. It needs

1128
01:09:08.770 --> 01:09:11.319
to respond to that harm to moral worth, so

1129
01:09:11.319 --> 01:09:13.750
refugees need to be viewed and treated with respect

1130
01:09:13.750 --> 01:09:19.648
as moral equals, um, and also, Um, conditions should

1131
01:09:19.648 --> 01:09:21.368
be secured in which they're viewed and treated as

1132
01:09:21.368 --> 01:09:24.368
moral equals by others, and there needs to be

1133
01:09:24.368 --> 01:09:29.229
this human rights protection in order to, um, address

1134
01:09:29.229 --> 01:09:31.868
the rightlessness that they experience. So I think that

1135
01:09:31.969 --> 01:09:35.167
then is the proper understanding of positive duties towards

1136
01:09:35.167 --> 01:09:35.408
them.

1137
01:09:37.149 --> 01:09:40.959
So I have one final question or topic I

1138
01:09:40.959 --> 01:09:44.910
would like to explore here. So are there any

1139
01:09:44.910 --> 01:09:52.910
circumstances or instances where the states can violate human

1140
01:09:52.910 --> 01:09:56.770
rights in regards to how they treat refugees?

1141
01:09:58.859 --> 01:10:02.290
Do you mean Are there any circumstances in which

1142
01:10:02.290 --> 01:10:05.399
it would be permissible for states to violate human

1143
01:10:05.399 --> 01:10:05.629
rights?

1144
01:10:06.200 --> 01:10:07.200
Yes, exactly, yeah.

1145
01:10:07.939 --> 01:10:10.660
I mean this may relate to a question we

1146
01:10:10.660 --> 01:10:16.629
spoke about earlier where. We might think that. Rights

1147
01:10:16.629 --> 01:10:23.029
provide strong constraints against actions towards persons, um, but

1148
01:10:23.029 --> 01:10:25.870
they might not necessarily be absolute constraints. We might

1149
01:10:26.149 --> 01:10:30.109
think that there could be some extreme circumstances in

1150
01:10:30.109 --> 01:10:33.830
which it might be permissible, um, to violate rights

1151
01:10:33.830 --> 01:10:36.790
in order to prevent some moral catastrophes such as

1152
01:10:36.790 --> 01:10:39.669
like the deaths of many millions of people or

1153
01:10:39.669 --> 01:10:44.589
some such. But I think it's going to be

1154
01:10:44.589 --> 01:10:49.810
very hard, if not impossible, to justify the violating

1155
01:10:49.810 --> 01:10:53.870
of refugees' human rights that we currently see as

1156
01:10:53.870 --> 01:10:58.910
a result of state practices because such violations, as

1157
01:10:58.910 --> 01:11:03.089
I suggested earlier, are are not necessary, proportionate, um,

1158
01:11:03.669 --> 01:11:08.879
and they're against innocent persons. And I think this.

1159
01:11:10.450 --> 01:11:13.569
So I, I, in principle, yes, but I can't

1160
01:11:13.569 --> 01:11:18.000
foresee any circumstance, um. In in the real world

1161
01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:20.379
in, in, in which that would be permissible, no.

1162
01:11:21.330 --> 01:11:25.819
Mhm. No, that, that's fair enough. So, uh, the

1163
01:11:25.819 --> 01:11:29.970
book is again, the ethics of state Responses to

1164
